Here’s the exact prompt you can give to GitHub Copilot (or Copilot Chat) to generate the query you need:


---

✅ Prompt to Ask Copilot:

> I have two PostgreSQL tables:

1. pc_common.location_mapping
    – mapping_code_type (varchar)
    – mapping_code (varchar)


2. pc_common.psc_site_code_info
    – location_code_type (varchar)
    – location_code (varchar)



I want a SQL query that checks for any duplicate combinations of (code_type, code_value) where:

mapping_code_type + mapping_code in location_mapping

and location_code_type + location_code in psc_site_code_info


These pairs must be globally unique across both tables.
The query should return any (code_type, code_value) combination that appears more than once across the union of both tables.




---

If you want to include which table the duplicates are from, add:

> Also include a column in the result to indicate whether the duplicate came from location_mapping, psc_site_code_info, or both.




---

Let me know if you want the SQL query directly written instead of generating it from Copilot.
